    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "Jeremi and Zachary, with Dr. Sean Theriault discuss congressional politics and question whether the U.S. Senate should continue to have a rule for a Filibuster."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": ""
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "Dr. Sean Theriault is a professor in the Department of Government at the University of Texas at Austin. He is a leading scholar of American political institutions, and the U.S. Congress in particular. Sean has published five books: "
        },
        {
          "text": "Congress: The First Branch",
          "italic": true
        },
        {
          "text": " (with Mickey Edwards; Oxford University Press, 2020), "
        },
        {
          "text": "The Great Broadening",
          "italic": true
        },
        {
          "text": " (with Bryan Jones and Michelle Whyman; University of Chicago Press, 2019), "
        },
        {
          "text": "The Gingrich Senators",
          "italic": true
        },
        {
          "text": " (Oxford University Press, 2013), "
        },
        {
          "text": "Party Polarization in Congress ",
          "italic": true
        },
        {
          "text": "(Cambridge University Press, 2008), and "
        },
        {
          "text": "The Power of the People",
          "italic": true
        },
        {
          "text": " (Ohio State University Press, 2005). He has also published numerous articles in a variety of journals on subjects ranging from presidential rhetoric to congressional careers and the Louisiana Purchase to the Pendleton Act of 1883."
        }
